  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and evolved over several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged in response to organized crime activities in the early 20th century\n- Initially focused on disguising proceeds from illegal activities like bootlegging and gambling\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States first established reporting requirements\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established international standards\n\n3. International Development:\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n- Expanded global cooperation and standardized anti-money laundering regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n4. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded money laundering regulations\n- Increased surveillance and reporting requirements\n- Linked money laundering prevention to terrorism financing prevention\n\n5. Modern Legal Framework:\n- Comprehensive international regulations\n- Strict reporting requirements\n- Significant penalties for non-compliance\n- Ongoing adaptation to technological changes like cryptocurrency\n\nThe legal framework continues to evolve with emerging financial technologies and global economic shifts.",
